I love mountain biking as much as the next guy. I even enjoy slapping a GoPro on various parts of my bike and person to get sweet action shots and verbally muse about the trail. What I cannot abide is the constant barrage of spiders and their webs. Oh, believe me, that won't stop me from riding, but I am not ashamed to say that I go out of my way to avoid large webs and stop frequently to de-web. A cursory search of how to remedy this problem gets results like "wear a full face mask if it bothers you that bad" and "brown recluses don't live in trees." That's all well and good but I'm not wearing goggles or a full face for summer xc riding. So what's the solution? I hope these three suggestions will help you during the inevitable spider-pocalypse.&nbsp;

1. Find a Patsy to ride in front of you.&nbsp;

This may not always be possible, but it is definitely the most effective spider repellent. I like to ride with a couple friends and we get on a rotation during the ride taking "spider duty" as the front man. Usually I take point the whole time when I bring a new person on their first few rides.&nbsp;

2. Find the best time of day for your area

Maybe you can go after a popular riding time when all the webs will be down. Or maybe you're lucky enough that that is usually the case except for a pre work ride. Maybe the spiders in your area are less active at certain times of the day. Try different times and find what works best for you during the summer months when they are at their worst.&nbsp;

3. Engineer a spider catcher

I've seen a few of these ranging from a well placed stick in the bars to helmet mountain field goal posts. If you can stand to look very strange on the trail, then why the heck not. Or maybe you can get a friend to make one and go in front of you.&nbsp;

If you have any good spider stories or preventative methods that work for you, let me know!
